The music Nigeria includes many kinds folk and popular music some which are known worldwide Styles folk music are related the multitudes ethnic groups the country each with their own techniques instruments and songs Little known about the countrys music history prior European contact although bronze carvings dating back the 16th and 17th centuries have been found depicting musicians and their instruments The largest ethnic groups are the Igbo Hausa and Yoruba Traditional music from Nigeria and throughout Africa almost always functional other words performed mark ritual such wedding funeral and not achieve artistic goals Although some Nigerians especially children and the elderly play instruments for their own amusement solo performance otherwise rare Music closely linked agriculture and there are restrictions for example which instruments can played during different parts the growing season Work songs are common type traditional Nigerian music They help keep the rhythm workers fields river canoes and other fields Women use complex rhythms housekeeping tasks such pounding yams highly ornamented music the northern regions farmers work together each others farms and the host expected supply musicians for his neighbours The issue musical composition also highly variable The Hwana for example believe that all songs are taught the peoples ancestors while the Tiv give credit named composers for almost all songs and the Efik name individual composers only for secular songs many parts Nigeria musicians are allowed say things their lyrics that would otherwise perceived offensive The most common format for music Nigeria the callandresponse choir which lead singer and chorus interchange verses sometimes accompanied instruments that either shadow the lead text repeat and ostinato vocal phrase The southern area features complex rhythms and solo players using melody instruments while the north more typically features polyphonic wind ensembles The extreme north region associated with monodic singleline music with emphasis drums and tends more influenced Islamic music The people the North are known for complex percussion instrument music the onestringed goje and strong praise song vocal tradition Under Muslim influence since the 14th century Hausa music uses freerhythmic improvisation and the Pentatonic scale similar other Muslim Sahelian tribes throughout West Africa such the Bambara Kanuri Fulani and Songhai Traditional Hausa music used celebrate births marriages circumcisions and other important life events Hausa ceremonial music well known the area and dominated families praise singers The Hausa play percussion instruments such the tambura drum and the talking drum The most impressive the Hausa state instruments however the elongated state trumpet called Kakaki which was originally used the Songhai cavalry and was taken the rising Hausa states symbol military power Kakaki trumpets can more than two metres long and can easily broken down into three portable parts for easy transportationNura inwa The Igbo people live the southeast Nigeria and play wide variety folk instruments They are known for their ready adoption foreign styles and were important part Nigerian highlife The most widespread instrument the 13stringed zither called obo The Igbo also play slit drums xylophones flutes lyres udus and lutes and more recently imported European brass instruments Courtly music played among the more traditional Igbo maintaining their royal traditions The ufie slit drum used wake the chief and communicate meal times and other important information him Bell and drum ensembles are used announce when the chief departs and returns his village Meal times may include pie and other dessert foods for the holidays The Yoruba have drumming tradition with characteristic use the dundun hourglass tension drums Ensembles using the dundun play type music that also called dundun These ensembles consist various sizes tension drums along with kettledrums gudugudu The leader dundun ensemble the iyalu who uses the drum talk imitating the tonality Yoruba Much Yoruba music spiritual nature and devoted their God Yoruba music has become the most important component modern Nigerian popular music result its early influence from European Islamic and Brazilian forms These influences stemmed from the importation brass instruments sheet music Islamic percussion and styles brought Brazilian merchants both the Nigerias most populous city Lagos and the largest city Ibadan these multicultural traditions were brought together and became the root Nigerian popular music Modern styles such Alhaji Sikiru Ayinde Barristers fuji Salawa Abenis waka and Yusuf Olatunjis sakara are derived primarily from Yoruba traditional musicYoruba music have now come age and the new generation Nigerian music now sing their native language 9ice one many that broke into the industry with Gongo Aso and many more artist followed Listening Timi Korus Babe Jowo and Flosha denotes artist home and abroad now rap and sing yoruba and not forgetting their heritage Nigerian theatre makes extensive use music Often this simply traditional music used theatrical production without adaptation However there are also distinct styles music used Nigerian opera Here music used convey impression the dramatic action the audience Music also used literary drama although its musical accompaniment more sparingly used than opera again music communicates the mood tone events the audience example John Pepper Clarks The Ozidi Saga play about murder and revenge featuring both human and nonhuman actors Each character the play associated with personal theme song which accompanies battles which the character involved Traditional Nigerian theatre includes puppet shows Borno State and among the Ogoni and Tiv and the ancient Yoruba Alrnj tradition which may descended from the Egngn masquerade With the influx roadbuilding colonial powers these theatre groups spread across the country and their productions gr